              ],
              "free_text": [
                ""
              ]
            }
          ],
          "DETECTOR": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": [
                "MCPLT",
                "IOCH"
              ],
              "free_text": [
                " The Los Alamos Neutron Science Center",
                "employing the SPectrometer for Ion DEtermination in",
                "fission Research (SPIDER)."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "SAMPLE": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "Each source consists of an electroplated Cf sample",
                "that is permanently fixed into an aluminum capsule of",
                "12.7-mm diameter x 6.36-mm height. The capsule has",
                "a thin gold window (100 microg/cm2) that allows alpha",
                "particles and fission fragments to exit the sample",
                "without losing significant energy. During the",
                "experiment, the activity of each source was about",
                "1 microCi."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "METHOD": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "SPIDER was developed for measuring independent FPYs,",
                "i.e. fission yields after the prompt neutron emission",
                "but before beta-decay, in direct-kinematics using the",
                "double energy-double velocity (2E-2v) method. In the",
                "2E-2v method, the masses of both fission fragments",
                "are determined by measuring their kinetic energy and",
                "velocity. This method has several advantages compared",
                "to other direct kinematics techniques, like the",
                "double-energy (2E) and electromagnetic separation, as",
                "it enables the measurement of multiple correlated",
                "fission quantities, such as pre and post-neutron",
                "emission FPYs with high mass resolution (~1 AMU),",
                "total kinetic energy (TKE), and prompt neutron",
                "multiplicity. In contrast to the 2E method, the 2E-2v",
                "method measures the independent FPY's directly,",
                "without relying on theoretical inputs for neutron",
                "emission."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "ERR-ANALYS": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": {
                "heading": "ERR-S",
                "minimum_value": null,
                "maximum_value": null,
                "correlation_property": null
              },
              "free_text": [
                " The standard errors."
              ]
            },
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": {
                "heading": "ERR-SYS",
                "minimum_value": null,
                "maximum_value": null,
                "correlation_property": null
              },
              "free_text": [
                " The main source of systematic uncertainty",
                "is the mass calibration. The given systematic errors",
                "were estimated based on the 95% confidence band (2-",
                "sigma) of the calibration line, which is shown in",
                "Figure 7."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "CORRECTION": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "Empirical corrections for energy losses and PHDs are",
                "difficult to apply with the desired level of accuracy,",
                "as they depend on the mass, charge, and energy of the",
                "fission fragments. As a result, FPY measurements that",
                "rely on this type of correction usually suffer from",
                "large systematic uncertainties."
              ]
            }
          ],
